{{use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} {{Redirect|Alexandra Stadium|the stadium in Pennsylvania|Ross Memorial Park and Alexandre Stadium}} {{Infobox Stadium | stadium_name = Gresty Road | image = [[Image:Gresty Road, Crewe.jpg|256px|View from the north eastern corner of the ground after Crewe Alexandra's defeat by Reading, 4 February 2006 (photo by Andrew Smith)]] | fullname = Alexandra Stadium | nickname = The Crest, The Stainton | built = 1906 | opened = 1906 | surface = Grass | seating_capacity = 10,153 | tenants = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] | dimensions = 112 x 74 yards | record_attendance = 20,000 }}
'''Alexandra Stadium''', more commonly known as '''Gresty Road''' is a [[Association football|football]] [[stadium]] in [[Crewe]], [[Cheshire]], England. The home ground of [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], it has an all-seated capacity of 10,153.
==History== Crewe had initially played at the [[Alexandra Recreation Ground]], also on Gresty Road and located just to the north of current site. After leaving the ground towards the end of the [[1895–96 Football League|1895–96 season]] the club played at a variety of venues, including in nearby [[Sandbach]], before moving to the original Gresty Road ground in 1897.<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888–2005'', Yore Publications, p13, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref>
In 1906 the ground was demolished to make way for the construction of new railway lines, and a new Gresty Road ground was built directly to the west of the site.<ref name=UD/> The new ground initially had a stand on each touchline, one of which had been moved from the first Gresty Road ground, and some embankments around the remainder of the pitch.<ref name=UD2>Smith & Smith, p62</ref> After a fire, a new Main Stand was built on the south side of the ground in 1932. The record attendance of 20,000 was set on 30 January 1960 for an [[FA Cup]] match against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]].<ref name=UD2/>
In the 1990s Gresty Road was rebuilt, with all-seater stands constructed on all four sides of the ground.<ref name=UD2/>
On 31 May 2015, the ground held an international friendly match between [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] and [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Northern Ireland to play Qatar in Crewe friendly|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31906366|accessdate=21 March 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=16 March 2015}}</ref>
==Stands== *'''Air Products Stand''' ''(formerly the Railtrack Stand before a change in sponsorship)'' – built prior to the 1999–2000 season at a cost of £5.2 million. It accommodates 6,809 spectators, together with the club's office accommodation. *'''Mark Price Stand''' – also known as the ''Gresty Road End'', accommodates 982 spectators and four disabled spectators. *'''Wulvern Housing Stand''' – also known as the ''Railway End'', accommodates 682 spectators. *'''[[Whitby Morrison]] Ice Cream Van Stand''' – formerly ''the Pop'', originally the Popular Side, accommodates 1,680 away spectators.
