'''Spartan Cricket Club''' is a cricket club in [[Barbados]].
Spartan was formed in 1893 as a club for [[middle-class]] black and creole cricketers who were denied entry into all-white cricket clubs such as [[Wanderers Cricket Club|Wanderers]] and [[Pickwick Cricket Club|Pickwick]].<ref>Sandiford, p. 11.</ref> The inaugural president of the club was Sir [[William Conrad Reeves]], Chief Justice of Barbados and other members consisted mostly of "lawyers, medical practitioners, elite schoolmasters, higher level civil servants and the few non-whites to have penetrated the managerial levels of the business, commercial and plantation worlds."<ref>Stoddart, pp. 327&ndash;328.</ref> The club played its matches at the Belleville ground in [[Saint Michael, Barbados|Saint Michael]] and the first captain of the club was [[George Learmond (cricketer)|George Learmond]].<ref name=Sandiford12>Sandiford, p. 12.</ref>
Cricket in Barbados at the time was strictly divided by colour and class. Spartan was seen as a middle-class club and in its early years efforts to admit working-class cricketers met with some resistance. In 1899, the club was divided about the admission of [[Fitz Hinds]]&mdash;a talented cricketer who had previously worked as a groundsman at Pickwick Cricket Club. After his admission, many of his team-mates refused to play with him.<ref name=Sandiford12/> The club was split again in 1913 when [[Herman Griffith]] attempted to join the club. Considered "too poor to enter", he was denied admission. This attitude distressed a significant minority of the club who split and established a club for working-class blacks, [[Empire Cricket Club]] in 1914. Spartan and Empire developed a strong rivalry.<ref name=Sandiford16>Sandiford, p. 12.</ref>
Before and after Barbadian independence, members of Spartan Cricket Club were influential members of Barbadian society, including [[Grantley Adams]], the first Premier of Barbados.<ref>Stoddart, p. 328 "Interviewees invariably pointed to the fact that all post-independence Governors-General and Prime Ministers have been Spartan men, not to mention a preponderance of politicians and senior civil servants."</ref> It is claimed that Spartan has "produced more <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[West Indies]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> [[Test cricket]]ers than any other [club] in the Caribbean".<ref name=Benn>{{cite news|last=Wilde|first=Simon|title=Wisdom of Sulieman Benn|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/cricket/article5733170.ece|accessdate=30 June 2011|newspaper=Sunday Times|date=15 February 2009}}</ref> The club now plays its games at Queen's Park in [[Bridgetown]].<ref name=QueensPark>{{cite news|last=Brenkley|first=Stephen|title=Timely rock for cradle of the Caribbean|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cricket/timely-rock-for-cradle-of-the-caribbean-558859.html|accessdate=30 June 2011|newspaper=The Independent|date=4 April 2004}}</ref>
Notable cricketers from Spartan include: *Sir [[Clyde Walcott]].<ref name=Walcott>{{cite news|title=Sir Clyde Walcott|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/sir-clyde-walcott-413679.html|accessdate=30 June 2011|newspaper=The Independent|date=28 August 2006|quote= The young Walcott also began playing for the famous Spartan Club ...}}</ref> *[[Wes Hall]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Berry|first=Scyld|title=Never a cricketer of the year|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/395673.html|work=Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|publisher=ESPNCricinfo|accessdate=30 June 2011|year=2008|quote=Tony Cozier opened the batting for Lodge School against Hall, playing for Spartan ...}}</ref> *[[Sulieman Benn]].<ref name=Benn />
==Notes== {{Reflist}}
==References== *{{cite book|last=Sandiford|first=Keith A. P.|title=Cricket Nurseries of colonial Barbados: The elite schools 1865-1966|year=1998|publisher=The Press University of the West Indies|location=Kingston|isbn=976-640-046-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IcxYwq0sB_8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Cricket+nurseries+of+colonial+Barbados&hl=en&ei=5zYMTuyfLMH1mAXvwJW9Dg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false}} *{{cite journal|last=Stoddart|first=Brian|title=Cricket, Social Formation and Cultural Continuity in Barbados: A Preliminary Ethnohistory|journal=Journal of Sport History|year=1987|volume=14|issue=3|url=http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH1987/JSH1403/jsh1403d.pdf|accessdate=30 June 2011}}
