{{Infobox sporting event organization |name = State Games of America |image = |size = |caption = |image2 = |size2 = |caption2 = |abbreviation = SGA |motto = |formation = 1999 |recurrence = Biennial |last = |purpose = |location = [[Lynchburg, VA (2019)]] |leader_title = |leader_name = |website = [http://stategamesofamerica.com/] |remarks = }}
The '''State Games of America''' is a [[wikt:biennial|biennial]] [[Amateur sports|amateur]] [[multi-sport event]] held in [[North America]]. It is organized by the [[National Congress of State Games]].<ref name="State Games Home">{{Citation|title=2011 State Games of America|url=http://www.calstategames.org/sga-home.html|accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> Athletes qualify for the Games by earning a [[medal]] in their respective State Games in the previous two years.<ref name="W-S Journal">{{Citation|title=State Games celebrating 25 years in North Carolina|url=http://www2.journalnow.com/news/2011/jun/17/wsmet01-state-games-celebrating-25-years-in-north--ar-1128769/year=2011|author=Collins, Dan|journal=Winston-Salem Journal|accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> Typically, over 12,000 athletes compete in the Games each time they are held.<ref name="ESPN Article">{{Citation|title=Colorado Springs lands state games again|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=oly&id=2437605|year=2006|journal=Associated Press|accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref>
==History== {| class="wikitable" |- ! Year !! Host City |- | 1999 || [[St. Louis, Missouri]] |- | 2001 || [[St. Louis, Missouri]] |- | 2003 || [[Hartford, Connecticut]] |- | 2005 || [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]] |- | 2007 || [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]] |- | 2009 || [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]]<ref name="Cal Games">{{Citation|title=State Games of America|url=http://www.calstategames.org/sga-aboutus.html|year=2011|accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> |- | 2011 || [[San Diego, California]] |- | 2013 || [[Hershey, Pennsylvania]]<ref name="Ala Sports">{{Citation|title=State Games of America|url=http://www.alagames.com/index.php?page=info_sga|journal=Alabama Sports Festival|accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> |- | 2015 || [[Lincoln, Nebraska]]<ref name="Nebraska Sports Council">{{Citation|title=State Games of America|url=http://www.sga2015.com/|year=2015|accessdate=2014-06-15}}</ref> |- | 2017 || [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]]<ref name=2017games>On the [http://www.stategamesofamerica.com 2017 State Games of America website], '''click on''' "Sport Listing." Retrieved 2016-10-23.</ref> |- | 2019 || [[Lynchburg, Virginia]] |- | 2021 || [[Ames, Iowa]] |}
==Sports contested== In 2011, athletes participated in 24 different sports in [[San Diego, California]]:<ref name="Event Schedule">{{Citation|title=State Games of America|url=http://www.stategames.org/State_Games_of_America.html|year=2011|author=National Congress of State Games|accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref>
{{Col-begin}} {{Col-break}} * [[Archery]] * [[Badminton]] * [[Baseball]] * [[Basketball]] * [[BMX]] * [[Bowling]] * [[Figure Skating]] * [[Gymnastics]] * [[Judo]] * [[Lifeguard#Lifeguard competitions|Jr. Lifeguards]] * [[Karate]] * [[Power Lifting]] {{Col-break}} * [[Skateboarding]] * [[Soccer]] * [[Softball]] (Girls Fast Pitch) * [[Surfing]] * [[Swimming (sport)|Swimming]] * [[Synchronised swimming]] * [[Table Tennis]] * [[Taekwondo]] * [[Track and Field]] * [[Water Polo]] * [[Olympic weightlifting|Weightlifting]] * [[Wrestling]] {{col-end}}
